🧠 What Is a Kernel?

The kernel is the core part of an operating system.
It acts as a bridge between:
Applications  ↔  Hardware
Applications cannot directly talk to hardware.They must go through the kernel.

🏗️ Simple Architecture
Application (Chrome, Java, MySQL)
↓
Kernel (Linux / Windows Kernel)
↓
Hardware (CPU, RAM, Disk, Network)

🖥️ Traditional System Architecture
Application Layer -> Host OS kernel-> Hardware 
Applications directly use: System calls, OS kernel services and Drivers

🐳 Docker Architecture
Applications (inside containers)
↓
Docker Engine
↓
Host OS Kernel (shared)
↓
Hardware

🔑 Key Point:
Docker does NOT include its own kernel.
It uses:
👉 The host machine’s kernel

Containers share the same kernel but are isolated using: Namespaces, cgroups and Union file systems

💻 Virtual Machine Architecture
Applications
↓
Guest OS (Full OS with its own Kernel)
↓
Hypervisor
↓
Host OS
↓
Hardware

Each VM contains:
Full OS
Separate kernel
System libraries

⚡ Why Docker Is Lightweight
Docker:
Shares host kernel
No separate OS
Image size: MBs
Starts in seconds

VM:
Includes full OS
Separate kernel
Image size: GBs
Takes minutes to boot

🧠 Deep Technical Explanation
1️⃣ Kernel Sharing

Docker uses Linux kernel features:
namespaces → process isolation
cgroups → resource control
overlayfs → layered filesystem
So container = isolated process.

VM = fully virtualized machine.

